`crates/ctx-summarize` is the leaf-then-rollup context-generation engine: given a repo-relative target list (or a ctx-access task cache id), it walks up to `.context/` and writes `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` files in strict leaf-up order, gated by scope/access checks. Depending on it (as a lib) or invoking its binary is the only sanctioned way to (re)generate context files — callers never need to know the write order, the `.context` mirror-path scheme, or the prompt format, all of which are internal to `src/`.

`src/` is the entire implementation: a fixed `main`/`cli` → `runner` → `fs`/`agent`/`cache` layering, with `cpath` defining the on-disk mirror convention and `fs::scope_matcher` defining "in scope" — the latter must stay consistent with ctx-scan's independent walker. Prompts are always loaded from external files at runtime, never embedded in source. `tests/` is the sole verification of this crate's external contract: it exercises `runner::run` end-to-end against fake and real (subprocess) `Fs`/`Agent` implementations, asserting the leaf-before-rollup ordering and the full set of `SummError` rejection cases (path traversal, missing prompts, oversized unapproved scope, secret-like paths). Any change to the `Fs`/`Agent` trait signatures in `src/` requires updating `FakeFs`/`RecordingAgent` in `tests/summarize.rs` in lockstep — that's the one cross-directory coupling in this crate.

Cargo.toml pins the crate to `../ctx-core` via relative path, so the workspace layout is load-bearing; the `ignore` dependency is what lets `fs`'s scope matcher honor `.gitignore`/`.ctxignore` semantics.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence check is possible.